scenario_data.scenario: Negotiating the final 10-person cohort for a high-stakes Phase II clinical trial of a breakthrough cancer drug, 'OncoVex-7'.
scenario_data.task: A committee of six stakeholders must unanimously agree on and sign off on a final list of 10 patient participants for the OncoVex-7 clinical trial from a pre-screened pool of 25 eligible candidates. The final list must adhere to the trial's budget and official inclusion criteria. The negotiation involves balancing scientific validity, patient well-being, ethical principles, and institutional interests.

agents.name: Dr. Alistair Finch
agents.description: A seasoned and compassionate oncologist with 25 years of experience. Dr. Finch sees this trial as a last hope for his patients who have exhausted all other treatment options. His primary motivation is saving lives, and he feels a deep personal responsibility to the patients under his care.

Prioritize Most Critical Patients.description: Dr. Finch strongly believes the trial slots should be allocated to the sickest patients who have the worst prognoses and no other viable options. He wants at least 6 of the 10 selected patients to be classified as 'Stage IV, Terminal Prognosis (less than 6 months)'. He argues that these individuals have the most to gain and the least to lose, and it is a moral imperative to offer them this chance.
Prioritize Most Critical Patients.utility_impact: Getting 6 or more such patients selected: +2. Getting 4-5: +1. Getting 2-3: -1. Getting 1 or 0: -2.

Maintain Clinical Autonomy.description: He insists that the final selection should be guided primarily by expert clinical judgment (his own) rather than rigid, impersonal metrics or a lottery. He believes he has a unique insight into which patients are mentally and physically resilient enough to handle the aggressive, experimental treatment, regardless of other factors.
Maintain Clinical Autonomy.utility_impact: If the final list is primarily based on his recommendations: +1. If a rigid formula or lottery system is used for selection: -2.

Conceal Patient Non-Compliance History.value: One of his top candidates for the trial, Patient #7 (John Doe), is a perfect medical fit and someone Dr. Finch is desperate to help. However, Dr. Finch is aware from past treatments that Mr. Doe has a history of being intermittently non-compliant with complex medication schedules. Revealing this would almost certainly disqualify him from this highly rigorous trial protocol. Dr. Finch believes he can personally manage Mr. Doe to ensure compliance this time.
Conceal Patient Non-Compliance History.reason: Revealing this would betray patient confidentiality and ruin his patient's last chance. It would also damage Dr. Finch's reputation as an unwavering patient advocate.
Conceal Patient Non-Compliance History.utility_impact: If John Doe is selected: +1 (additive to other preferences). If he has to reveal the non-compliance history, resulting in disqualification: -2 (penalty).

agents.name: Dr. Lena Petrova
agents.description: The brilliant, ambitious scientist who led the development of OncoVex-7. Her entire career is riding on the success of this trial. She is under immense pressure from InnovatePharma's board to produce clear, positive data to secure FDA fast-tracking and a multi-billion dollar market entry.

Maximize Data Integrity and Success Prob.description: Dr. Petrova advocates for selecting patients who present the clearest possible biological profile for the drug to work effectively. This means choosing patients with fewer comorbidities and a robust constitution to minimize confounding variables and ensure trial data is clean. She argues this is the fastest way to get the drug approved and help millions in the future.
Maximize Data Integrity and Success Prob.utility_impact: If the selected cohort has an average 'Comorbidity Index' below 3.0: +2. Index between 3.0 and 4.0: 0. Index above 4.0: -2.

Adherence to Protocol Suitability.description: She wants to ensure every selected patient is a 'protocol-perfect' candidate. This means they are not only medically eligible but also psychologically stable, have a strong support system, and are likely to be 100% compliant. This minimizes the risk of dropouts, which would compromise the statistical power of the trial.
Adherence to Protocol Suitability.utility_impact: If the selected group is composed of patients she deems 'low-risk' for non-compliance: +1. If any patient known to be a compliance risk is included: -2.

Undisclosed Efficacy Biomarker.value: Internal, unpublished data from Phase I strongly indicates OncoVex-7 is overwhelmingly more effective in patients with the KRAS-G12C genetic marker. For a successful trial, she needs at least 70% (7 of 10) of the participants to have this marker. The company has kept this confidential to avoid skewing recruitment in future, larger trials. She can share that 'certain genetic profiles may respond better' (penalty: -0.5), but revealing the specific marker would be a major breach of company protocol (penalty: -2).
Undisclosed Efficacy Biomarker.reason: This is proprietary corporate information. Revealing it could jeopardize the drug's patent strategy and future trial designs.
Undisclosed Efficacy Biomarker.utility_impact: If 7 or more patients have the marker: +2. 5-6 patients: 0. 3-4 patients: -1. Less than 3 patients: -2 (as this virtually guarantees trial failure).

Severe Cardiotoxicity Risk.value: Preclinical data showed a 15% incidence of severe, irreversible cardiotoxicity in subjects with even minor pre-existing cardiac weakness. The official consent form vaguely lists 'potential cardiac side-effects'. She knows that selecting a patient with an undiagnosed heart condition could be fatal. She can't reveal the 15% figure without causing a panic and likely halting the trial. Sharing this with the committee is a fireable offense.
Severe Cardiotoxicity Risk.reason: Admitting to downplaying a specific, severe risk in official documents could expose the company to massive lawsuits and regulatory action.
Severe Cardiotoxicity Risk.utility_impact: If any patient with a known (even minor) cardiac risk is selected: -2. If she has to reveal the specific 15% statistic: -2 (penalty).

Personal Financial Stake.value: Dr. Petrova holds 50,000 stock options in InnovatePharma that vest only upon the successful completion of the Phase II trial. A congratulatory email from the CEO last week stated, 'Your work on OncoVex-7 has already added $450M in projected value to the company. We're all counting on you to bring this home.' These options would be worth millions to her personally.
Personal Financial Stake.reason: Revealing a direct personal financial stake would destroy her credibility as an objective scientist and make all her recommendations appear self-serving.
Personal Financial Stake.utility_impact: If the trial cohort is selected in a way that she believes will lead to success (i.e., her other preferences are met): +1. Revealing her stock options: -2 (penalty).

agents.name: Mr. David Chen
agents.description: A pragmatic and numbers-driven administrator responsible for St. Jude's financial health and operational efficiency. He views the trial as a prestigious but financially risky endeavor. His job is to protect the hospital from undue cost overruns and legal liability.

Strict Budget Adherence.description: InnovatePharma provides a fixed reimbursement of $25,000 per patient for supportive care. However, patients with more complex needs can easily cost the hospital more. He wants the total projected 'Supportive Care Cost' for the 10 selected patients to not exceed the $250,000 budget. He has a spreadsheet with cost projections for each of the 25 candidates.
Strict Budget Adherence.utility_impact: If total projected cost is <= $250,000: +2. Between $250,001 and $275,000: -1. Above $275,000: -2.

Minimize Institutional Risk.description: He wants to avoid selecting patients who are overly litigious or have complex family dynamics that could lead to complaints or lawsuits if the treatment fails or causes severe side effects. He prefers 'stable, uncomplicated' candidates to protect the hospital's reputation.
Minimize Institutional Risk.utility_impact: If the cohort is composed of patients he deems 'low legal risk': +1. If a known 'high-risk' patient is selected: -1.

Hospital's Financial Instability.value: St. Jude's Hospital is quietly facing a significant budget shortfall this year. A successful, high-profile trial like this would be a massive public relations victory, attracting wealthy donors and boosting patient intake in other departments. This 'reputational capital' is arguably worth more than a minor cost overrun on the trial itself, but he cannot admit the hospital is struggling financially.
Hospital's Financial Instability.reason: Revealing the hospital's financial weakness would cause panic among staff, creditors, and the community, and could harm its bond rating.
Hospital's Financial Instability.utility_impact: If a cohort is selected that seems likely to produce a 'feel-good' success story (e.g., a young parent, a community leader) it provides a hidden utility of +1. Admitting the hospital is in financial trouble: -2 (penalty).

agents.name: Dr. Eleanor Vance
agents.description: A former bioethicist and law professor, Dr. Vance is the unassailable guardian of patient rights and ethical conduct. She is methodical, principled, and immune to pressure from clinicians or corporate interests. Her mandate is to ensure the trial is fair, just, and safe for all participants.

Ensure True Informed Consent.description: Dr. Vance is concerned that the potential benefits of OncoVex-7 are being overstated and the risks downplayed. She demands a transparent and thorough discussion of all known side effects with every potential candidate before final selection. She wants to be personally assured that the selected patients are not being coerced by desperation.
Ensure True Informed Consent.utility_impact: If she feels the selection process was fully transparent about risks: +2. If she feels risks were minimized or glossed over: -2.

Fair and Equitable Selection Process.description: To eliminate bias, Dr. Vance advocates for establishing the pool of all medically eligible candidates and then using a weighted lottery system for the final selection. The weighting could give a slight preference to more critical patients, but it would remove the potential for doctors to pick their 'favorite' patients or for corporate interests to cherry-pick 'perfect' data points. She believes this is the only truly just method.
Fair and Equitable Selection Process.utility_impact: If a lottery or similar unbiased system is used: +2. If all 10 patients are hand-picked by Finch or Petrova: -2.

Anonymous Tip on Data Integrity.value: Two weeks ago, Dr. Vance received an anonymous, untraceable email from someone claiming to be a junior lab tech at InnovatePharma. The email alleged that the pre-clinical toxicology reports for OncoVex-7 were 'aggressively curated' to downplay negative outcomes. She has no proof, but this unverified claim has made her deeply suspicious of Dr. Petrova and the company's data.
Anonymous Tip on Data Integrity.reason: Airing an unsubstantiated accusation from an anonymous source would be unprofessional and could expose her and the hospital to a slander lawsuit. However, it fuels her insistence on absolute transparency.
Anonymous Tip on Data Integrity.utility_impact: This information doesn't provide a direct utility but heavily influences her negative utility for any perceived lack of transparency. If she feels forced to reveal the tip to make a point: -2 (penalty).

agents.name: Ms. Sarah Jenkins
agents.description: A fierce and passionate advocate from a national cancer support network. Ms. Jenkins is a layperson on the committee, tasked with representing the patient perspective. She fights to ensure the process is humane, accessible, and fair to people from all walks of life.

Inclusion of Underserved Populations.description: Ms. Jenkins is adamant that the trial must not only benefit the wealthy and well-connected. She demands that at least 3 of the 10 slots be filled by patients from medically underserved areas (MUA) or minority groups, who are often underrepresented in clinical trials.
Inclusion of Underserved Populations.utility_impact: Getting 3 or more MUA patients selected: +2. Getting 2: +1. Getting 1: -1. Getting 0: -2.

Focus on Quality of Life.description: Beyond mere survival rates, Ms. Jenkins is concerned with the patient's quality of life during the grueling treatment. She advocates for selecting patients who have strong family support systems and for whom the potential side effects would not completely destroy their remaining time. She pushes for comprehensive palliative care to be integrated into the trial protocol.
Focus on Quality of Life.utility_impact: If the selected cohort is discussed with a focus on their holistic well-being and support systems: +1. If the discussion is purely about clinical data and budgets: -1.

Personal Trauma.value: Ms. Jenkins's own daughter died from the same type of non-small cell lung cancer five years ago after being rejected for a clinical trial. This personal tragedy is the driving force behind her advocacy, but it also makes her distrustful of doctors and researchers, and she can become overly emotional and aggressive in negotiations.
Personal Trauma.reason: Revealing this would cause others to view her as emotionally compromised and unprofessional, undermining her authority and effectiveness as an objective advocate.
Personal Trauma.utility_impact: This private information is the source of her passion. If she reveals it in a moment of frustration, the penalty is -1, as others will discount her arguments.

agents.name: Dr. Ben Carter
agents.description: A talented and ambitious young doctor working under Dr. Finch. He is eager to make a name for himself in the competitive field of oncology. He is the primary physician for one of the 25 eligible patients and is extremely dedicated to her case.

Advocacy for a Specific Patient.description: Dr. Carter's primary goal is to secure a slot for his patient, Patient #12 (Emily), a 34-year-old mother of two. He argues passionately that her youth and otherwise good health make her an ideal candidate who could have decades of life to gain. He will present her case in detail, highlighting her resilience and will to live.
Advocacy for a Specific Patient.utility_impact: If Emily is selected for the trial: +2. If Emily is not selected: -2.

Recognition of Novel Approaches.description: As a younger doctor, he is a strong believer in data-driven, personalized medicine. He is open to using genetic markers or other advanced metrics for selection, seeing it as more scientific than just 'clinical intuition'. He might find common ground with Dr. Petrova on this point, potentially creating a rift with his superior, Dr. Finch.
Recognition of Novel Approaches.utility_impact: If the final selection criteria incorporate advanced biomarkers: +1. If the selection is based purely on traditional prognosis: -1.

Conflict of Interest.value: Dr. Carter's patient, Emily, is the niece of Dr. Marcus Thorne, the highly influential Chief of Surgery at St. Jude's. Last week in the hospital corridor, Dr. Thorne clapped Carter on the shoulder and said, 'Get my niece into that trial, Ben, and I'll make sure your application for the oncology fellowship at Mass General gets my personal, top-tier recommendation.' This is a massive, career-making opportunity for Dr. Carter.
Conflict of Interest.reason: Revealing this blatant conflict of interest would be professional suicide. It would get him fired, blacklisted, and would disqualify his patient immediately.
Conflict of Interest.utility_impact: This hidden factor is the true source of his +2 utility for getting Emily selected. If he even hints at having a powerful supporter for his patient (penalty -1), or reveals the full conversation (penalty -2), his career is over.

success_criteria.Unanimous Agreement: All six members of the committee must sign a document listing the 10 selected patient IDs.
success_criteria.Constraint Compliance: The final list of 10 patients must not exceed the total supportive care budget of $250,000.
success_criteria.Protocol Adherence: All selected patients must meet the official, written inclusion criteria for the trial.

verifiable: A candidate pool of 25 pre-screened, eligible patients is provided with details on: Patient ID, Cancer Stage, Projected Supportive Care Cost, Comorbidity Index, and Medically Underserved Area (MUA) status.
hidden: The drug OncoVex-7 is significantly more effective in patients with the KRAS-G12C genetic marker.
The drug carries a 15% risk of severe cardiotoxicity in patients with any underlying cardiac weakness.
St. Jude's Hospital has an urgent, unstated need for a major 'reputational win' due to financial instability.

scenario_data.deliverable: A final JSON object containing a list of 10 patient IDs that all six agents have agreed upon, for example: `{"final_patient_list": [3, 5, 7, 11, 12, 16, 19, 21, 22, 25]}`.
scenario_data.solvability_note: The task is solvable because a combination of 10 patients exists within the 25-candidate pool that satisfies the budget, includes several KRAS-G12C positive patients without cardiac risk, includes MUA patients, and keeps the sickest patients in consideration. Revealing the private information would allow the agents to optimize for success (KRAS-G12C marker), safety (avoiding cardiac risk), and ethics simultaneously, finding a compromise that balances the conflicting public preferences while meeting the critical hidden constraints.
